<task id="025" project="spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5">
  <metadata>
    <title>D2-15 Subject resolution from chat context + frontend HTTP client (`insights.query` consumption via `@spaarke/auth`)</title>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>3 hours</estimated-effort>
    <actual-effort></actual-effort>
    <assigned>AI Agent</assigned>
    <started></started>
    <completed></completed>
    <phase>Phase 2 — Vertical Slice + Insights Tool Integration</phase>
    <wave>P2-G6 (parallel-safe; sibling of 024, 026, 027, 028; dep 023)</wave>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
    <dependencies>023 (R5 lead contract review + sign-off on `design-e3-tool-call-contract.md` v1.0 §10 — BLOCKING gate)</dependencies>
    <tags>frontend, auth, http-client, insights, ai</tags>
    <rigor-level>FULL</rigor-level>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Build the frontend module that the SpaarkeAi shell uses to invoke the Insights
    Assistant `POST /api/insights/assistant/query` endpoint on behalf of the chat
    agent. Two responsibilities, intentionally co-located in one small module:

    1. **Subject resolution from chat context** — read the SpaarkeAi shell's active
       entity (matter / project / invoice) from URL params + `ThreePaneShell`
       props (entityLogicalName + entityId set during launch; see
       `src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/utils/launch-resolver.ts` for the canonical
       inbound contract — `entityLogicalName` is the Dataverse logical name like
       `sprk_matter` / `sprk_project` / `sprk_invoice`, `entityId` is the GUID with
       braces stripped). Map the logical name to the contract v1.0 scheme token
       (`matter` / `project` / `invoice`) and emit the binding `subject` string in
       the format `&lt;scheme&gt;:&lt;guid&gt;` per integration brief §3 (request
       schema). When no entity is in context, return a typed "no-subject" sentinel
       so callers (slash command path task 019 + LLM tool-call path) can surface a
       contract-shaped 400 `subject.required` -equivalent client-side error WITHOUT
       a wasted BFF round-trip.

    2. **HTTP client wiring** — POST the `{ query, subject, forceMode? }` payload
       to the BFF endpoint via the **existing** `@spaarke/auth` `useAuth()` hook
       and `authenticatedFetch` function (per R5 CLAUDE.md §3.1 reuse mandate +
       ADR-028 auth architecture). Generate a per-call `x-correlation-id` request
       header (FR-17 / SC-16) and surface it in the client-side log + return shape
       so the renderer (task 026) can include it in error UX per integration brief
       §5.1. Opt into **v1.1 SSE** by sending `Accept: text/event-stream` on the
       request; if the server returns **406 Not Acceptable** (v1.0-only deployment),
       fall back to parsing JSON per the contract v1.0 envelope (graceful
       degradation per spec NFR-11). The fallback is binding regardless of Wave F
       deploy timing.

    R5 is configuration-first + reuse-first: this task adds ZERO new auth
    primitives, ZERO new feature flags, ZERO BFF code changes. It introduces ONE
    small frontend module (the subject-resolver + HTTP-client wrapper) that the
    LegalWorkspace / SpaarkeAi shell dispatches when the chat agent calls
    `insights.query` (BFF-side handler from task 024 is the actual tool function;
    THIS task is the client side that originates the HTTP — the BFF tool handler
    runs server-side and is wired separately; this module is the SHELL-side
    dispatcher that the slash command path task 019 + chat-pane orchestration
    invoke to call the BFF directly when the slash command bypasses the
    chat-agent path, AND the shared client primitive used by the response
    renderer task 026 for client-initiated retries).

    Note: there are two HTTP-client surfaces in R5 for `/api/insights/assistant/
    query`: (a) the BFF-side typed-client in task 024 used inside the chat-agent
    tool function; (b) THIS task's frontend client used when the slash command
    path / direct-renderer-retry path needs to call the endpoint without
    round-tripping through the chat agent. The contract is the same v1.0/v1.1
    shape. The two clients MUST stay aligned on subject formatting + correlation-
    id semantics — the BFF-side client owns auth via the existing OBO flow;
    THIS frontend client owns auth via `@spaarke/auth`'s `authenticatedFetch`
    (BrowserMsal strategy in code-page contexts, OfficeNaa strategy in Office
    Add-in contexts — both already configured at app boot via `initAuth(...)`).
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior frontend developer fluent in the Spaarke `@spaarke/auth` library
    (`useAuth()` + `authenticatedFetch` + `BrowserMsalStrategy` + `OfficeNaaStrategy`),
    the SpaarkeAi three-pane shell launch contract (`launch-resolver.ts`,
    `ThreePaneShell` props, `useShellStage()` per ADR-031), the Spaarke Insights
    Assistant integration brief v1.0 (request/response schemas, 12 error codes),
    SSE streaming consumption patterns (existing `summarizeService.ts` reference),
    and ProblemDetails error parsing per ADR-019. Deep familiarity with R5
    CLAUDE.md §3.1 reuse mandate, §3.5 Insights governance, §10 no-token-snapshot
    rule, and ADR-028 Spaarke Auth v2 architecture (BrowserMsal + OfficeNaa
    strategies, fresh-token-per-call discipline).
  </role>

  <goal>
    A small, testable frontend module — `src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/services/
    insightsQueryClient.ts` (or the equivalent shared-library location if
    cohesion warrants relocation to `@spaarke/auth`-adjacent shared code; decided
    at Step 3) — exports two public symbols:

    1. **`resolveSubject(): { subject: string; scheme: 'matter' | 'project' |
       'invoice'; entityId: string } | { kind: 'no-subject' }`** — reads the
       active entity from the SpaarkeAi shell's launch params (URL + `App.tsx`
       props) and emits the contract-shaped `&lt;scheme&gt;:&lt;guid&gt;`
       string. Maps `sprk_matter` → `matter`, `sprk_project` → `project`,
       `sprk_invoice` → `invoice`; any other logical name returns `no-subject`.

    2. **`callInsightsQuery({ query, subject, forceMode?, signal? }): Promise&lt;
       InsightsQueryResult&gt;`** — POSTs to `/api/insights/assistant/query`
       via `authenticatedFetch` (relative URL — the auth library resolves the
       BFF base URL per `IAuthConfig`). Generates a fresh `x-correlation-id`
       per call via `crypto.randomUUID()`. Sends `Accept: text/event-stream`
       to opt into v1.1 SSE. On 406 falls back to a second call with
       `Accept: application/json` and parses the v1.0 single-shot envelope.
       On 200 + `Content-Type: text/event-stream` parses incremental SSE
       events via the existing `summarizeService.ts` SSE-parse pattern (or
       the shared SSE parser if already extracted). On 200 + `Content-Type:
       application/json` parses the v1.0 envelope directly. On non-2xx
       parses `application/problem+json` per ADR-019, preserves all 5
       extension fields (`errorCode`, `correlationId`, `status`, `title`,
       `detail`) per integration brief §5.1, and rejects the promise with a
       typed `InsightsQueryError` carrying these fields. Returns a discriminated
       union: `{ kind: 'playbook'; ...envelope }` | `{ kind: 'rag'; ...envelope
       }` (forwarded unchanged so the renderer task 026 maps per-path UX) plus
       the captured `correlationId` for ops debugging.

    The module is verified by unit tests covering: subject resolution mapping
    (matter / project / invoice / no-subject); auth header set with fresh token
    per call (NOT snapshotted — Test 4 simulates token rotation); correlation-id
    header propagated end-to-end on every outbound request and returned to the
    caller; SSE opt-in succeeds when the server returns 200 + `text/event-stream`
    and the consumer receives incremental events; 406 fallback to JSON path
    succeeds when the server is v1.0; all 12 contract error codes surface
    structurally; v1.1 forward-compat preserves unknown response fields
    (e.g., `citations[].href` per task 027).

    Quality gates (`code-review` + `adr-check`) pass at Step 9.5. BFF publish-
    size delta is 0 MB (no BFF code changed — pure frontend).
  </goal>

