    </files>
    <patterns>
      <pattern name="`useAuth()` consumption (canonical reference)" location="src/client/shared/Spaarke.Auth/src/useAuth.ts">
        Inside a React component, call `const { authenticatedFetch, getAccessToken } = useAuth();`. Call `authenticatedFetch(url, init)` per HTTP request — it returns the raw Response on 2xx and throws `ApiError` (with `.problemDetails`) on non-2xx or `AuthError` on auth failure after retries. Bearer header + 401 retry + ProblemDetails parsing are already handled. Use `getAccessToken()` directly only when `authenticatedFetch` cannot wrap (SSE `ReadableStream` lifecycle — but `authenticatedFetch` actually CAN handle SSE since it returns a `Response` whose body is a `ReadableStream`; verify at Step 4).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Relative URL → BFF base URL resolution" location="src/client/shared/Spaarke.Auth/src/authenticatedFetch.ts (lines 28–31, 88–94)">
        Pass a relative URL like `/api/insights/assistant/query`; `authenticatedFetch` resolves it against `provider.getConfig().bffBaseUrl` via `buildBffApiUrl`. Do NOT hand-concatenate the BFF base URL or duplicate the `/api/` prefix.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="ProblemDetails extraction from `ApiError`" location="src/client/shared/Spaarke.Auth/src/errors.ts + authenticatedFetch.ts">
        `ApiError` constructor receives `(message, status, problemDetails)`. In the `catch` block of the Insights client, narrow to `ApiError` (e.g., `if (err instanceof ApiError)`), extract `err.problemDetails`, then read `errorCode` (extension), `correlationId` (extension), `status`, `title`, `detail`. Re-throw a typed `InsightsQueryError` so callers can `instanceof`-check.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="SpaarkeAi launch params → entity context" location="src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/utils/launch-resolver.ts + src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/App.tsx">
        `App.tsx` receives `entityLogicalName` + `entityId` + `matterId` from URL params via `launch-resolver.ts`. Read these via either the props down-flow (preferred — cleaner contract) or via the same URL-param parsing used by `main.tsx`. For R5 the simplest pattern is: accept the entity context as a parameter passed in by the caller (chat-pane orchestration / slash command handler) rather than re-querying URL params inside the resolver — keeps the module pure + unit-testable.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Logical-name → contract scheme mapping" location="(new — defined inside this task's module)">
        Hardcode the mapping table inside this module:
        `const SCHEME_BY_LOGICAL_NAME: Record&lt;string, 'matter' | 'project' | 'invoice'&gt; = { 'sprk_matter': 'matter', 'sprk_project': 'project', 'sprk_invoice': 'invoice' };`
        Any other logical name → return `{ kind: 'no-subject' }`. Validate with a unit test covering all three known names + an unknown name + missing context.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="SSE consumption with content-type discrimination" location="(repo-wide SSE consumption precedent — search `summarizeService.ts` or equivalent if extracted)">
        After `authenticatedFetch` returns, inspect `response.headers.get('content-type')`. If it starts with `text/event-stream`, consume `response.body` as a `ReadableStream`, parse line-buffered SSE events (`event: ...`, `data: ...`, blank line terminator) per WHATWG EventSource spec. If `application/json`, call `response.json()` and parse the v1.0 envelope. Either path yields the same discriminated-union result type.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="406 fallback semantics" location="(spec NFR-11)">
        If `authenticatedFetch` throws `ApiError` with `status === 406`, retry the call once with `Accept: application/json` instead of `Accept: text/event-stream`. Treat any other non-2xx as a non-retryable error path. Keep the fallback path local — do NOT retry indefinitely (one retry only).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="v1.1 forward-compat passthrough" location="(integration brief §4 + v1.1 spec)">
        Define response DTOs with `[key: string]: unknown` index signature OR use `unknown` for the entire structured-result envelope shape and let the renderer (task 026) project the typed fields. The forward-compat goal: a v1.1 server that adds `citations[].href` does NOT require any changes in this task. Test 7 asserts unknown fields survive the round-trip.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Test colocation convention" location="src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/components/context/__tests__/ContextPaneController.test.tsx">
        Place unit tests under `__tests__/` adjacent to the module. Use the same Vitest / Jest test runner already configured in `src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/package.json`. Mock `authenticatedFetch` and `useAuth` at the module boundary; do NOT mock `provider.getAccessToken` internally — keep the test surface at the public auth API.
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      R5 ships a chat-driven "Summarize a Document" vertical slice AND the
      Insights tool integration (`insights.query`) through the SpaarkeAi
      three-pane shell. The Insights endpoint `POST /api/insights/assistant/
      query` is consumed from two distinct surfaces: (a) BFF-side, from inside
      the `InsightsQueryToolHandler` chat-agent tool function (task 024 —
      uses `IHttpClientFactory` typed-client + OBO from `HttpContext`); (b)
      Frontend-side, from the SpaarkeAi shell when the slash command path
      (`/ask-insights ...`, task 019) bypasses the chat-agent and dispatches
      directly to the endpoint, AND when the response renderer (task 026)
      needs to issue a client-initiated retry. This task (D2-15) ships
      surface (b).

      Both surfaces share the same v1.0/v1.1 contract (integration brief
      `notes/insights-engine-assistant-integration-brief.md` §3–§5 + v1.1
      negotiation `notes/insights-engine-contract-v1.1-request.md`). The
      contract is binding at v1.0; v1.1 (SSE for RAG-path `answer` streaming +
      clickable `citations[].href`) is Wave F deliverable currently in-flight
      via Claude Code on the Insights team branch (`work/ai-spaarke-insights-
      engine-r2-wave-f`). R5 ships with graceful v1.0 fallback per spec
      NFR-11 — this task's 406 fallback semantics are the binding mechanism
      for that contract.

      Subject resolution: the SpaarkeAi shell launches with an entity context
      (matter / project / invoice) carried in URL params per `launch-resolver
      .ts`. The launch contract is canonical — `entityLogicalName` is the
      Dataverse logical name (e.g., `sprk_matter`), `entityId` is the GUID
      with braces stripped. This task maps `sprk_matter` / `sprk_project` /
      `sprk_invoice` to the contract's scheme tokens (`matter` / `project` /
      `invoice`) and emits the binding `&lt;scheme&gt;:&lt;guid&gt;` string
      per integration brief §3. The mapping is one-way and exhaustive — no
      other logical names map to subjects. When no entity is in context
      (e.g., welcome stage before launch), the resolver returns a typed
      `no-subject` sentinel so the caller can surface a contract-shaped
      error WITHOUT a wasted BFF round-trip (avoids the 400 `subject.required`
      hit cycle).

      Auth: `@spaarke/auth` is the existing Spaarke Auth v2 library shipped
      across all frontend surfaces (Code Pages, PCF, Office Add-ins per
      ADR-028). `useAuth()` returns a function-based API (`getAccessToken`,
      `authenticatedFetch`) — intentionally NOT a token snapshot. The
      provider's in-memory cache returns fresh tokens per call; reactive
      updates are NOT a feature (see `useAuth.ts` line 36–46 comment). R5
      consumes the existing API exactly as documented; introduces ZERO new
      auth primitives.

      v1.1 SSE opt-in: the contract permits the server to choose response
      shape based on `Accept` header. Sending `Accept: text/event-stream`
      requests v1.1 SSE; server returns 200 + `Content-Type: text/event-
      stream` when v1.1 is deployed, or 406 Not Acceptable when only v1.0 is
      deployed. The client retries the 406 with `Accept: application/json`
      and parses the v1.0 envelope. The two response shapes are forwarded to
      the caller as a discriminated union (`{ kind: 'playbook'; envelope }`
      | `{ kind: 'rag'; envelope }`) — the SSE branch progressively yields
      `delta` events that the renderer (task 026) renders incrementally; the
      JSON branch yields a single resolved envelope.

      Correlation-id (FR-17 / SC-16): every Assistant turn carries a unique
      `x-correlation-id` end-to-end (client → BFF → Insights → AI services →
      back). This client generates the ID via `crypto.randomUUID()` for
      client-initiated calls (slash command path, direct retry); the BFF-side
      tool handler in task 024 generates its own when the call originates
      from the chat-agent tool function. Both surfaces forward the ID via the
