        shared module). Pros: future Office Add-in / PCF reuse without
        re-extraction. Cons: more upfront scaffolding (new package, build
        config) for a single consumer.

      **Default decision**: Candidate A. Per YAGNI + R5 CLAUDE.md §3.1 reuse
      mandate, do NOT create new shared-library packages without an existing
      multi-consumer need. Record the decision in task notes
      `notes/task-025-evidence.md`. If task 026's renderer would benefit from
      the client being importable from `@spaarke/ai-widgets`, revisit at
      task 026 time and migrate then.

      Define the public interface (TypeScript types) inside the module:

      ```ts
      export type SubjectScheme = 'matter' | 'project' | 'invoice';

      export interface ResolvedSubject {
        kind: 'subject';
        subject: string;        // `${scheme}:${entityId}` (canonical contract format)
        scheme: SubjectScheme;
        entityId: string;       // GUID without braces
      }

      export interface NoSubject {
        kind: 'no-subject';
      }

      export interface InsightsQueryRequest {
        query: string;          // 1..500 chars per contract §3.1
        subject: string;        // canonical `&lt;scheme&gt;:&lt;guid&gt;` format
        forceMode?: 'playbook' | 'rag';  // optional per FR-12 / SC-17
        // conversationContext intentionally omitted from v1.0 — server tolerates absence
      }

      export interface InsightsQueryPlaybookResult {
        kind: 'playbook';
        correlationId: string;
        envelope: Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;;  // structured envelope per integration brief §4.6
      }

      export interface InsightsQueryRagResult {
        kind: 'rag';
        correlationId: string;
        envelope: Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;;  // citation-grounded envelope per integration brief §4.6
      }

      export type InsightsQueryResult = InsightsQueryPlaybookResult | InsightsQueryRagResult;

      export class InsightsQueryError extends Error {
        constructor(
          public readonly errorCode: string,
          public readonly correlationId: string,
          public readonly status: number,
          public readonly title: string,
          public readonly detail: string,
          public readonly retryAfterSeconds?: number
        ) { super(`[${errorCode}] ${title}: ${detail}`); }
      }
      ```

      Record interface in task notes for cross-reference by task 026.
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Implement `resolveSubject` + `callInsightsQuery`">
      Create `src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/services/insightsQueryClient.ts`.

      **`resolveSubject(entityLogicalName?: string, entityId?: string):
      ResolvedSubject | NoSubject`** — accept the entity context as parameters
      (keeps the module pure + unit-testable; caller passes from
      `App.tsx`/`ThreePaneShell` props). Implementation:

      ```ts
      const SCHEME_BY_LOGICAL_NAME: Record&lt;string, SubjectScheme&gt; = {
        sprk_matter: 'matter',
        sprk_project: 'project',
        sprk_invoice: 'invoice',
      };

      export function resolveSubject(
        entityLogicalName?: string,
        entityId?: string,
      ): ResolvedSubject | NoSubject {
        if (!entityLogicalName || !entityId) return { kind: 'no-subject' };
        const scheme = SCHEME_BY_LOGICAL_NAME[entityLogicalName];
        if (!scheme) return { kind: 'no-subject' };
        // Strip braces defensively (launch-resolver already does this, but be safe)
        const cleanId = entityId.replace(/^\{|\}$/g, '');
        if (!cleanId) return { kind: 'no-subject' };
        return { kind: 'subject', subject: `${scheme}:${cleanId}`, scheme, entityId: cleanId };
      }
      ```

      **`callInsightsQuery({ query, subject, forceMode, signal }, fetch?:
      AuthenticatedFetchFn): Promise&lt;InsightsQueryResult&gt;`** —
      Implementation outline:

      1. Generate correlation ID: `const correlationId = crypto.randomUUID();`.
      2. Build the request body: `{ query, subject, ...(forceMode &amp;&amp;
         { forceMode }) }`. Do NOT include `forceMode` field when undefined
         (lets the server distinguish "not specified" from "specified as
         null").
      3. First attempt — opt into v1.1 SSE:
         ```ts
         const response = await (fetch ?? authenticatedFetch)(
           '/api/insights/assistant/query',
           {
             method: 'POST',
             headers: {
               'Content-Type': 'application/json',
               'Accept': 'text/event-stream',
               'x-correlation-id': correlationId,
             },
             body: JSON.stringify(body),
             signal,
           },
         );
         ```
         (Note: `authenticatedFetch` injects `Authorization: Bearer ...` on
         every call — fresh token per request per ADR-028.)
      4. If `authenticatedFetch` throws `ApiError` with `status === 406` —
         fallback path: retry once with `Accept: application/json` (same
         body, same correlation-id, same other headers). If the fallback
         path also fails, propagate.
      5. On success — inspect `response.headers.get('content-type')`:
         - If `text/event-stream` → consume SSE stream via `response.body`
           reader; parse line-buffered events; collate `delta` events into
           the envelope; on `complete` event emit the final result. (Detailed
           SSE-parse implementation: lines below.)
         - If `application/json` → `await response.json()` and parse the
           envelope; emit single-shot result.
      6. Discriminate result `kind`: read the `path` field from the response
         envelope (`"playbook"` or `"rag"` per integration brief §4) and
         return the appropriate discriminated-union shape with
         `correlationId` attached.
      7. On `ApiError` with non-406 status — extract `problemDetails`, throw
         a new `InsightsQueryError` preserving `errorCode`, `correlationId`
         (prefer the `correlationId` from `problemDetails` if present;
         fallback to the client-generated `correlationId`), `status`,
         `title`, `detail`, `retryAfterSeconds` (parsed from `Retry-After`
         response header on 429 if present).
      8. On `ApiError` with `status === 401` — server's 401 retry policy
         already runs inside `authenticatedFetch`; if we still got 401 here,
         it means auth is exhausted. Throw `InsightsQueryError` with
         synthetic `errorCode = 'auth.401'`.
      9. On `ApiError` with `status === 429` — extract `Retry-After`; throw
         `InsightsQueryError` with synthetic `errorCode = 'rate-limit.429'`
         + `retryAfterSeconds`.

      **SSE parsing detail** (inside `callInsightsQuery`):

      ```ts
      async function parseSseResponse(response: Response): Promise&lt;Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;&gt; {
        const reader = response.body!.getReader();
        const decoder = new TextDecoder();
        let buffer = '';
        let path: 'playbook' | 'rag' | null = null;
        const envelope: Record&lt;string, unknown&gt; = {};
        const deltaAccumulator: string[] = [];
        for (;;) {
          const { value, done } = await reader.read();
          if (done) break;
          buffer += decoder.decode(value, { stream: true });
          const events = buffer.split(/\n\n/);
          buffer = events.pop() ?? '';
          for (const ev of events) {
            const lines = ev.split(/\n/);
            const eventType = lines.find(l =&gt; l.startsWith('event: '))?.slice(7);
            const dataLine = lines.find(l =&gt; l.startsWith('data: '))?.slice(6);
            if (!dataLine) continue;
            const data = JSON.parse(dataLine) as Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;;
            if (eventType === 'delta') {
              deltaAccumulator.push(String(data.text ?? ''));
            } else if (eventType === 'complete') {
              Object.assign(envelope, data);
              path = (data.path as 'playbook' | 'rag') ?? path;
            } else if (eventType === 'metadata') {
              Object.assign(envelope, data);
              path = (data.path as 'playbook' | 'rag') ?? path;
            }
          }
        }
        if (deltaAccumulator.length &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; envelope.answer === undefined) {
          envelope.answer = deltaAccumulator.join('');
        }
        return envelope;
      }
      ```

      Use this consumer-mode SSE parser for the simple R5 dispatch case. For
      progressive rendering (task 026's renderer needs incremental events),
      task 026 may switch to a generator/observer-based variant; this client
      provides the resolved-envelope variant as the baseline.

      Add `getAccessToken` as an optional second parameter signature for
      callers that need SSE with a different lifecycle (per `useAuth.ts`
      line 9–11 SSE-escape-hatch comment) — but document that
      `authenticatedFetch` is the canonical path and `getAccessToken` direct
      use is reserved for non-fetch network primitives (none exist in R5
      scope).

      Document the public API in JSDoc on each exported symbol so VS Code
      hover surfaces the contract semantics + ADR-028/FR-17/FR-16 references.

      Verify Zone B boundary by grep — the new file MUST NOT import any
      types from `src/server/api/...` paths.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Wire the client into the slash command path (touchpoint validation)">
      The slash command path (`/ask-insights`, task 019) is the primary
      client-side invoker. Task 019 produces the slash command handler; this
      task's responsibility is to expose a clean `callInsightsQuery` API +
      verify it is consumable from the slash command handler shape.

      Document the integration contract in `notes/task-025-evidence.md`:
      - Slash command handler reads the current entity context from
        `App.tsx` props (`entityLogicalName` + `entityId`); calls
        `resolveSubject(entityLogicalName, entityId)`; if `kind === 'no-
        subject'` surfaces a client-side `subject.required`-shaped error to
        the user (chat-pane orchestration handles UX); otherwise calls
        `callInsightsQuery({ query, subject, forceMode })` where `forceMode`
        is set by the slash sub-command (`/ask-insights playbook ...` →
        `forceMode: 'playbook'`; `/ask-insights rag ...` → `forceMode:
        'rag'`; bare `/ask-insights ...` → `forceMode: undefined`).
      - The renderer (task 026) reads the result and dispatches to playbook
        vs RAG view per `result.kind`. Errors surface via `InsightsQueryError`
        → per-code UX (integration brief §5.1 column 4).

      Do NOT modify slash command code in this task (that is task 019's
      surface); just verify the integration contract is consumable. Cross-
      reference the typeshape with task 019's POML when authoring.
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Author tests (subject resolution, fresh-token-per-call, correlation-id, SSE, 406 fallback, error codes, forward-compat)">
      Create `src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/services/__tests__/insightsQuery
      Client.test.ts` with the project's existing test runner (Vitest per
      SpaarkeAi convention).

      - **Test 1 (subject resolution — happy paths)**: `resolveSubject('sprk_
        matter', 'abc-123')` → `{ kind: 'subject', subject: 'matter:abc-123',
        scheme: 'matter', entityId: 'abc-123' }`. Repeat for `sprk_project` →
        `project` and `sprk_invoice` → `invoice`.
      - **Test 2 (subject resolution — no-subject paths)**: `resolveSubject(
        undefined, undefined)` → `{ kind: 'no-subject' }`. `resolveSubject(
        'sprk_matter', undefined)` → `{ kind: 'no-subject' }`. `resolveSubject(
        'sprk_account', 'abc-123')` → `{ kind: 'no-subject' }` (unmapped
        logical name). `resolveSubject('sprk_matter', '{abc-123}')` →
        braces stripped → `'matter:abc-123'`.
      - **Test 3 (callInsightsQuery — v1.1 SSE happy path)**: Mock
        `authenticatedFetch` to return a `Response` with `Content-Type:
        text/event-stream` + a stub `ReadableStream` body emitting:
        `event: metadata\ndata: {"path":"rag","correlationId":"abc"}\n\n`,
        `event: delta\ndata: {"text":"Hello "}\n\n`, `event: delta\ndata:
        {"text":"World"}\n\n`, `event: complete\ndata: {"answer":"Hello
        World","citations":[]}\n\n`. Assert: returned `{ kind: 'rag',
        correlationId: '&lt;client-generated&gt;', envelope: { path: 'rag',
        correlationId: 'abc', answer: 'Hello World', citations: [] } }`.
        Assert the request was sent with `Accept: text/event-stream` and
        `x-correlation-id: &lt;uuid&gt;`.
      - **Test 4 (no-token-snapshot — fresh token per call)**: Mock
        `authenticatedFetch` to record the call sequence. Issue two
        sequential `callInsightsQuery` invocations; mock `getAccessToken`
        (via the mock `authenticatedFetch` indirection) to return distinct
        tokens (`tokenA` first call, `tokenB` second call — simulates
        rotation). Assert each outbound `Request` carries the
        correctly-rotated token (or, equivalently, that
        `authenticatedFetch` is called twice — once per invocation — and
        the wrapper does NOT close over a cached token from the first
        call). This validates the §10 / ADR-028 no-token-snapshot rule.
      - **Test 5 (correlation-id propagation)**: Assert each call generates
        a unique `crypto.randomUUID()` value, sets it as `x-correlation-id`
        request header, and returns it as `result.correlationId`. Two
        successive calls produce two distinct IDs.
      - **Test 6 (v1.0 JSON path — direct, no fallback)**: Mock returns 200 +
        `Content-Type: application/json` with a v1.0 envelope `{path:
        "playbook", structuredResult: {...}, correlationId: "xyz"}`. Assert
        returned `{ kind: 'playbook', correlationId: '&lt;client-generated&gt;',
        envelope: {...} }`.
      - **Test 7 (406 fallback to JSON)**: Mock first call (with `Accept:
        text/event-stream`) returns 406; mock second call (with `Accept:
        application/json`) returns 200 + JSON v1.0 envelope. Assert: two
        outbound calls were made, second with `Accept: application/json`,
        result correctly populated. Correlation-id is reused across the
        two calls (same client-generated value).
      - **Test 8 (12 error codes mapping)**: For each of the 12 contract
        error codes (integration brief §5.1), mock `authenticatedFetch` to
        throw `ApiError` with the appropriate ProblemDetails payload.
        Assert `callInsightsQuery` throws `InsightsQueryError` preserving
        `errorCode`, `correlationId` (from problemDetails), `status`,
        `title`, `detail`. Codes: `query.required`, `subject.required`,
        `subject.invalid`, `forceMode.invalid`, `conversationContext.
        invalid`, `auth.401` (synthetic), `rate-limit.429` (synthetic with
        retryAfterSeconds extracted), `ai.insights.disabled`, `ai.rag.
        disabled`, `ai.intent-classification.disabled`, `ai.assistant-
        default-playbook.unconfigured`, `INSIGHTS_ASSISTANT_INTERNAL_ERROR`.
      - **Test 9 (forceMode semantics)**: `forceMode: undefined` → field
        omitted from request body; `forceMode: 'playbook'` → field set in
        request body; `forceMode: 'rag'` → field set; client does NOT
        pre-validate values (a hypothetical `'garbage'` would be forwarded
        — but TypeScript type narrows to `'playbook' | 'rag'` so this is a
        compile-time guard, not a runtime one — document this).
      - **Test 10 (v1.1 forward-compat)**: Mock returns 200 with extra
        unknown fields (`citations[0].href = 'https://...'`, top-level
        `streaming: true`, `confidence: 0.42`). Assert all unknown fields
        survive in `result.envelope` unchanged (`Record&lt;string,
        unknown&gt;` index-signature pass-through).
      - **Test 11 (Zone B boundary grep)**: Programmatic test reading the
        module source file content; assert no `import ... from 'src/server/
        api/...'` or `../server/...` strings appear. Implement via Node's
        `fs.readFileSync` on the source path or via an import-graph
        analysis if a repo convention test exists.
      - **Test 12 (Cancellation via AbortSignal)**: Pass an `AbortController.
        signal` to `callInsightsQuery`; abort mid-call; assert the call
        rejects with a typed cancellation error (DOMException `AbortError`
        passthrough is acceptable — does NOT need to be wrapped in
        `InsightsQueryError`).

      Run `npm test` (or whichever Vitest invocation matches the SpaarkeAi
      project's `package.json` `scripts.test`); all 12 tests MUST pass.
